<li id="c7">
  <div class="cx" id="cx50291340">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">I agree that there are two issues, as Klein said.</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1212198/50291340#c7?mode=alone;showrate=1#c7">6+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:142501">nextstep</a>, <a href="/user/uid:5179">Adam B</a>, <a href="/user/uid:193700">sethtriggs</a>, <a href="/user/uid:92953">VClib</a>, <a href="/user/uid:320847">AmericanAnt</a>, <a href="/user/uid:31366">Dallasdoc</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>I think, however, that some people here would have more credibility if the, like Klein, recognized this fact:<br /></p>
<blockquote>He properly distinguished between the partisan targeting of Tea Party groups, which is wrong and dangerous as an IRS activity</blockquote>
Sometimes I see people, especially some people here, try to ignore that point and jump immediately to point two: &nbsp;that the IRS had an obligation to investigate groups that raised scrutiny on grounds OTHRER THAN the fact that they had conservative ideologies. &nbsp;
<p>When you respond to point 1 solely by jumping immediately to point 2 (without any recognition of the completely unacceptable and dangerous action by the IRS in point 1), it sounds like you are trying to rationalize away point 1. &nbsp;And that looks hypocritical, implying that it's ok to do it to them because they are conservative anyway. &nbsp;</p>
<p>If you really believe both points, you should want rectification of both points. &nbsp;You can advocate for stronger limits on 501(c)(4) status. &nbsp;Absolutely. &nbsp;Completely. &nbsp;But you also must want a full investigation to find out who it was at the IRS that initiated, or instigated, the "wrong and dangerous" activity by the IRS. &nbsp;That "wrong and dangerous" activity is a huge concern in and of itself. &nbsp;</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig"></p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:120104">coffeetalk</a> on <a href="/comments/1212198/50291340#c7">Wed May 29, 2013 at 07:33:49 AM PDT</a></p>
