<li id="c8">
  <div class="cx" id="cx50291373">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">I agree with you</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1212198/50291373#c8?mode=alone;showrate=1#c8">8+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:170696">skillet</a>, <a href="/user/uid:199851">TRPChicago</a>, <a href="/user/uid:71575">arlene</a>, <a href="/user/uid:214512">Auriandra</a>, <a href="/user/uid:143843">bobatkinson</a>, <a href="/user/uid:75006">DSPS owl</a>, <a href="/user/uid:193700">sethtriggs</a>, <a href="/user/uid:154504">jfromga</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>People who claim that political targeting by the IRS, at whatever level, is not a scandal are just plain wrong. &nbsp;They're letting partisan blinders obscure the obvious.</p>
<p>There are four aspect to this scandal:<br />
1. Local targeting of right-wing groups for investigation, which is a scandal.<br />
2. &nbsp;Investigation of targeted groups, which so far appears entirely proper.<br />
3. Granting these groups 501c4 status, which is much more of a scandal.<br />
4. Political grandstanding by Republicans and immediate caving by the president, which are dishearteningly familiar.</p>
<p>It's useful to keep all these separate aspects in mind, because they all have very distinct implications.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig">
If you want to cut Social Security, you're not a real Democrat.
</p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:31366">Dallasdoc</a> on <a href="/comments/1212198/50291373#c8">Wed May 29, 2013 at 07:38:22 AM PDT</a></p>
  <p class="cl">
  
 
 
  [ <a href="#c7">Parent</a> ] 
    
   

 
 
 </p> 
  </div>
  </div>
</li> 


	


	<ul id="k50291373" class="cm i1">




<li id="c9">
  <div class="cx" id="cx50291458">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">Addressing them as separate issues is </span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1212198/50291458#c9?mode=alone;showrate=1#c9">5+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:841008">Pi Li</a>, <a href="/user/uid:236557">Pilotshark</a>, <a href="/user/uid:214512">Auriandra</a>, <a href="/user/uid:75006">DSPS owl</a>, <a href="/user/uid:92953">VClib</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>key, it seems to me.</p>
<p>When you <strong>immediately</strong> move to "but groups with political ideologies shouldn't get 501(c)(4) status and the law should be changed," &nbsp;It looks like you are trying to change the subject, or sweep scandal #1 under the rug. &nbsp;Trying too hard to link the two makes it looks like you are implying that what the IRS did was ok, it's just the law that's bad. &nbsp;</p>
<p>By the way, whether scandal #1 was "local" is part of the issue. &nbsp;Remember, the Cinn office was the national office for 501(c)(4)'s. &nbsp;And Sekulow (who is filing an extensive federal complaint this morning) says he has letters and documentation from other offices, from Washington, and signed by Levin. &nbsp;We'll have to see. &nbsp;</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig"></p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:120104">coffeetalk</a> on <a href="/comments/1212198/50291458#c9">Wed May 29, 2013 at 07:48:22 AM PDT</a></p>
  <p class="cl">
  
 
 
  [ <a href="#c8">Parent</a> ] 
    
   

 
 
 </p> 
  </div>
  </div>
</li> 


	


	<ul id="k50291458" class="cm i1">




<li id="c11">
  <div class="cx" id="cx50291776">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">Political ideology on its face is an alert flag.</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1212198/50291776#c11?mode=alone;showrate=1#c11">3+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:154504">jfromga</a>, <a href="/user/uid:143843">bobatkinson</a>, <a href="/user/uid:824659">Old Sailor</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>What activities the group seeking preferential tax treatment proposes to engage in - and will, in fact do - with its ideology is very much the business of the IRS.</p>
<p>That, to me, is the <u>first</u> question about applying for tax exempt status.</p>
<p>In this charged environment, <u>among</u> the next questions are:</p>
<p>- Have groups with conservative ideologies been selected <u>disproportionately</u> for scrutiny?</p>
<p>- Have they included in their application the purposeful "tests" the <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/27/us/politics/nonprofit-applicants-chafing-at-irs-tested-political-limits.html?pagewanted=all&amp;_r=0"><em>New York Times</em> article</a> reported? (i.e. invited scrutiny to test the law, to get publicity that Fox &amp; Co. is so willing to give?)</p>
<p>I'm willing to believe a reputable lawyer's representations about facts, but the fact that he represents 27 conservative groups who have filed applications for 501c status suggests he might not only be knowledgable but a very involved party and possibly (!) even an advocate.</p>
<p>What is hurting the IRS now is its failure to come forth. True, it doesn't usually disclose operational details, but this is an inherently contentious area (whatever ones ideology). These charges are serious and deserve more visibility.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig">
