<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:154504">jfromga</a>, <a href="/user/uid:156548">Larsstephens</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>There are no stats on this that I know of. The issue is - did the IRS disproportionately target conservative groups for extra analysis? Over the past few years, it would not be at all surprising if the universe of 501c applications has been heavily skewed with conservative groups.</p>
<p>But if there are trigger words and phrases - and yes, your chosen name can be a signal - that suggest political activity, it is absolutely a fair question (and under the existing regs, a necessary one) about the nature and extent of political activities.</p>
<p>Bottom line: I don't think the IRS "is not supposed to target [insert species] for ideology." I don't think the IRS should be walled off from inquiring about the political activities of a politically ideological group <u>for the purposes of granting or refusing tax exempt status.</u></p>
<p>Tea Party preceding "Sewing Circle" or "Health Club" or "Tea Party Activists Book Club" - without a declaration of purposes or activities &nbsp;(the 501c application form asks for this) that touch politics - shouldn't invoke more scrutiny than would normally be triggered by the rest of the application and the organizing documents that are attached. &nbsp;For example, Question 15 on the IRS form asks:</p>
<blockquote>Has the organization spent or does it plan to spend any money attempting to influence the selection, nomination, election, or appointment of any person to any Federal, state, or local public office or to an office in a political organization? If “Yes,” explain in detail and list the amounts spent or to be spent in each case.</blockquote>
But if the name is, say, "Tea Party Activists of NW Illinois" or "Progressive Activists of NW Illinois", the IRS does not have to be made blind or stupid about what to look for or what more to ask.

