<p>I would think that the (hypothetical) application of the "Committee to Reelect the President" for 501(c)(4) status should go to the "give this one a closer look" pile right away.</p>
<p>I think you are confusing profiling (usually racial) with applying rational criteria. &nbsp;The name of a 501(c)(4) applicant is not chosen in a vacuum; &nbsp;the name, in and of itself, conveys meaningful information about the activities of the applicant.</p>
<p>Furthermore, there is a question on Form 1024 that asks, "Has the organization spent or does it plan to spend any money attempting to influence the selection, nomination, election, or appointment of any person to any Federal, state, or local public office or to an office in a political organization." &nbsp;If a Tea Party (or Progress Now affiliate) answered yes to that question, it clearly would have &nbsp;warranted further scrutiny to determine if it complies wiht the limits on electoral activity. &nbsp;On the other hand, if it answered no to that question, it also would have warranted further scrutiny, since it was pretty clear that Tea Party affiliates were heavily involved in electoral activity.</p>

