<p>What is at issue here is that, at some point, the IRS ALSO started screening for extra scrutiny based on words used in the name -- and all the words used in the screening were words associated with conservative ideology. In other words, if you used the words "tea party," "patriot,' or "9/12" in your name, you were very likely to be selected for extra scrutiny <em>regardless of whether there was anything in your application that merited extra scrutiny</em>. That's what the IRS admitted to. &nbsp;That was completely indefensible. &nbsp;</p>
<p>The better question would be, of the groups selected for extra scrutiny <em>based on a word used in the name</em> (rather than something in their application that was flagged), how many were conservative groups?</p>

  </div>
