<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:92953">VClib</a>, <a href="/user/uid:120104">coffeetalk</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>If an organization were strictly a social benefit organization such as general education, providing health services, medical research, helping the poor, garden club, etc., it would file as 501(c)(3), so its contributors could deduct contributions on their personal income tax returns - which should make a significant increase in their donations, and not being able to engage in electoral politics would not be much of a constraint on what they want to do.</p>
<p>If the organization wanted to be exclusively trying to elect people to office they would file as 501(c)(5). &nbsp;Donors do not get a tax deduction and donor information is made public.</p>
<p>Organizations choose to be 501(c)(4), so they can engage in politics and ideology and even electoral politics and not be required to make donor information public while donors do not get a tax deduction on their contributions. &nbsp;The restriction however is that spending directly on elections must be less than 50%.</p>
<p>As a piratical matter, approving 501(c)(4)s is an issue of campaign finance and whether the donors are publicly disclosures, it is not about what taxes the government collects. &nbsp; If the organization is not approved for a 501(c)(4), it either cuts back on electoral politics so it does qualify or it becomes a 501(c)5.</p>
<p>This is why you will not find 501(c)(4)s that are not political.<br /></p>

  </div>
