<p>How can the IG reach a conclusion, print it in the report, and state that the criteria was set and never reviewed by more than first level management initially and that was wrong, if they didn't know from looking at the files, memos, etc who set the policy? &nbsp;If you read the footnotes to the report, it never names a person's name, but it even names the numbers of people who were on the specialist teams (originally one person, there is a lot of your delay right there), etc.</p>
<p>The Administration has done nothing to hinder any investigation. &nbsp;I never said that Congress couldn't investigate. &nbsp;I merely pointed out the widely known disfunctional nature of the House oversight under Issa.</p>
<p>What you keep saying is there has been no investigation, what you keep wanting is to further the notion of a need for a witch hunt. &nbsp; They are actually different things.</p>
<p>Anyone can say the administration did something. &nbsp; The IRS is an administrative agency enforcing statutes, so Congress has control and oversight of its rule making functions and the power to fund the agencies, the executive has the job of administering the funding and staffing &nbsp;of these agencies and making them do their work. &nbsp;It is an interesting hybrid system, but not quite accurate to say that Congress has oversight of the 'executive branch' in the sense of the President and his functions as assigned by the Constitution, as they are separate and co-equal branches under the Constitution. &nbsp;</p>
