  <div class="ct">
  
<p>Yes, it is often the case that when people -- including lower-level processors -- feel overwhelmed by the sheer volume of work they are facing, they take shortcuts. &nbsp;And it is logical to believe that one or more lower-level processors decided on their own to address the applications with "tea party" or similar words in the titles. &nbsp;</p>
<p>One of the things that bugs me is the (arrogant) assumption that lower-level employees have no minds of their own and do things precisely as they are instructed. &nbsp;But it could well be that the lower-level employees watch television or read the Internet or newspapers, draw their own conclusions about which applicants are most likely trying to get away with something (i.e., the tea party) and sort through and tackle their respective workloads accordingly. &nbsp;</p>
<p>There <em>is no need</em> to automatically assume that President Obama or some senior official instructed the processors to discriminate. &nbsp;There <em>is need</em> to understand that people at all levels think independently and tend to arrange their work in a way they find manageable, regardless of the specific official policies and procedural guidelines. &nbsp;</p>

